<h1 align="center">ğŸŒ Google Cloud Platform (GCP) Resource Hierarchy</h1>

<p align="center" style="font-size: 18px;">
Google Cloud Platform (GCP) organizes its resources in a <b>hierarchical structure</b> 
to help manage <b>access control</b>, <b>billing</b>, and <b>policies</b> efficiently.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>ğŸ—ï¸ Hierarchy Overview :</h2>

<p style="font-size: 16px;">
The hierarchy has <b>four main levels</b> (from top to bottom):
</p>

<p style="font-size: 18px; text-align:center;">
<b>Organization â†’ Folder(s) â†’ Project(s) â†’ Resource(s)</b>
</p>

<hr>

<h2>ğŸ” 1. Organization (Root Node)</h2>

<ul style="font-size: 16px;">
<li><b>Top-most node</b> in the hierarchy.</li>
<li>Represents your entire company or domain, e.g. <code>example.com</code>.</li>
<li>Policies (like IAM roles or organization policies) set here apply to <b>everything below</b>.</li>
<li>Managed by <b>Organization Administrators</b>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>ğŸ—‚ï¸ 2. Folders</h2>

<ul style="font-size: 16px;">
<li>Optional layer to <b>group projects</b> logically.</li>
<li>Can be nested to reflect departments, teams, or environments 
(e.g., <i>Finance â†’ Production â†’ GCP Project</i>).</li>
<li>Useful for delegating admin rights to departments or managing policy inheritance.</li>
</ul>

<h2>ğŸ“¦ 3. Projects</h2>

<ul style="font-size: 16px;">
<li>The <b>core unit</b> of resource organization and management in GCP.</li>
<li>Every GCP resource (VM, storage bucket, etc.) must belong to a <b>single project</b>.</li>
<li>Each project has:
  <ul>
    <li><b>Project ID</b> (unique globally)</li>
    <li><b>Project Name</b></li>
    <li><b>Project Number</b></li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li>Billing, APIs, and IAM roles are managed at the <b>project level</b>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>âš™ï¸ 4. Resources</h2>

<ul style="font-size: 16px;">
<li>These are the <b>actual GCP services</b> you create and use â€” like Compute Engine VMs, 
Cloud Storage buckets, BigQuery datasets, etc.</li>
<li>They live <b>inside a project</b>.</li>
<li>Access control is inherited from the project and above.</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>ğŸ” IAM Policy Inheritance</h2>

<ul style="font-size: 16px;">
<li>IAM (Identity and Access Management) <b>policies cascade down</b> the hierarchy.</li>
<li>A role granted at the <b>Organization level</b> applies to all folders, projects, 
and resources beneath it.</li>
<li>Lower levels can override or add more specific roles.</li>
</ul>
